Return Codes and Exit Status

Every command returns an exit status
Range from 0 to 255
0 = success
Other than 0 = error conditions
Use for error checking
Use man or info to find meaning of exit status

$? -- contains the return code of the previously executed command.

Host=”google.com
ping -c 1 $Host

if [ “$?” -eq “0” ]
then
  echo “$Host reachable.”
else
  echo “$host unreachable.”
fi

Host=”google.com”
ping -c 1 $Host

if [ “$?” -ne “0” ]
then
  echo “$Host unreachable.”
fi

Host=”google.com”
ping -c 1 $Host
RETURN_CODE=$?

If [ “$RETURN_CODE” -ne “0” ]
then
  echo “$Host unreachable”
fi


&& AND 
Check for both condition should True then return True and return OutPut.

|| OR
Check for any one of condition should True then return OutPut 

#! /bin/bash
Host=”google.com”
ping -c 1 $Host && echo “$Host reachable.”

The Semicolon ;
If you want to perform multiple command in a single line then use “;”

cp test.txt /tmp/bak ; cp test.txt /tmp

# Same As:
cp test.txt /tmp/bak/
cp test.txt /tmp


Exit Command
Explicitly define the return code

exit 0
exit 1
exit 2
exit 255

#!/bin/bash
Host=”google.com”
ping -c 1 $Host

if [ “$?” -ne “0” ]
then
  echo “$Host unreachable.”
  exit 1
fi
exit 0

